(2117, 932, 'eskra', 'nope@hotmail.com', '', '174.21.240.167', '2010-05-06 14:23:16', '2010-05-06 22:23:16', 'Are these questions sincere, or are you just trying to make your point by putting words in the authors'' mouths?\r\n\r\nAssuming you''re sincere, and speaking only for myself, an anarchist who finds a lot to agree with in the text:\r\n\r\n"you would oppose expanding the floor of the cage?"  No.\r\n"you would oppose minimum wage increases?" No.\r\n"you would oppose shortened workdays?" No.\r\n"you would oppose giving respirators to campus custodians because they''re still working within existing capitalist institutions?"  No.\r\n\r\nBut demanding these specific reforms, or else we''ll halt "business as usual," instead of earnestly seeking to end business forever, doesn''t remind me of anarchist struggle.\r\n\r\nIf you read the pamphlet, it''s clear that the authors are arguing that we should look beyond reforming the system and aim for liberation.  This has always been the "rich tradition" of anarchist struggle.  Nowhere in the text does it imply that the authors are against reforms themselves, but instead against setting the limits of our struggle in terms of demands and reformism, which the system can easily defeat or recuperate.  \r\n\r\n"You''ve read guy debord"--and if you have, too, you know that a major focus of his work was to analyze why every revolution (besides the capitalist one) has failed; agreeing ahead of time to return to our roles maintaining capitalism if its ruling class agrees to be softer and kinder is one reason.\r\n\r\nWe should be critical of aims, strategies, and tactics of struggles as we participate in them.  You say, apparently without irony, "this is lame sectarian bullshit, not THE anarchism I love," (emphasis mine) and question whether the authors are really anarchists.  I wonder if your anxiety over what is the correct kind of anarchism has kept you from critiquing what the writing actually says.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10.4; en-US; rv:1.9.1.9) Gecko/20100315 Firefox/3.5.9', '', 0, 0),
