(2151, 932, 'sew', 'sarah.wht1@gmail.com', '', '174.21.253.213', '2010-05-10 12:42:51', '2010-05-10 20:42:51', 'I am also an anarchist organizing around budget cuts  at UW, and like Ariel and SK, I am disappointed and uninspired by this pamphlet.  Of course I agree that liberation and not recuperation must be our ultimate aim and that we must be critical of the movements we participate in, especially since capitalism has shown a remarkable ability to absorb threats by co-opting them.  Like the authors, I also want us to break out of our cages and upend the board!  \r\n\r\nBut this pamphlet misconstrues the organizing at UW and makes an easy critique that borders on an attack of UW Student Worker Coalition (SWC) without  asking the more difficult questions about what we should be doing in our organizing.     \r\n\r\nThe authors fail to see the university as a workplace, and in doing so treat budget cuts organizing at UW as a "student movement."  Yes, the university teaches students to be consumers of their own lives, but it is also a hella exploitative boss for many low-wage and immigrant workers on campus( and many undergrads and grad students like myself who have low paying campus jobs).  Custodians were at the forefront of this struggle last year when they organized to stop cuts to swing-shift, and budget cuts organizing at UW continues to be a student AND a worker movement.  We are fighting as workers, and when we are fighting for student demands, it is always in solidarity with and alongside workers!  I recognize that this was a mistake and was not malicious, but it also shows me that the authors are probably not deeply engaged in organizing at UW. Both SK and Ariel''s responses show why this oversight is so damaging:  it masks the struggles for workplace democracy of already invisibilized workers and trivializes demands based on workers'' material needs.  \r\n\r\nI also agree that SWC, as a student and WORKER coalition, is reformist in its orientation, if not to the extent of organizations that isolate students from workers or politely beg the legislature or administration for pittances.  You''re not telling us anything we don''t know or aren''t upfront about. But it''s really, really easy to trash real-life organizing as reformist, and it''s so much more difficult to figure out how we should instead be organizing towards liberation.  \r\n\r\nYou start with relatively concrete (if somewhat inaccurate) critiques of the "student movement" at UW,  and then you retreat into nice-sounding slogans that I mostly agree with but that are abstracted from the real struggles of students and especially workers.  This is an easy out, and it enables the authors to trash our organizing work without ever having to go out on a limb and suggest (let alone organize towards) any alternatives.  I''m not saying that short- and long-term "plans" for the revolution have to be filed alongside any critique of existing organizing work, but a piece that dismisses all budget cuts organizing at UW out of hand without suggesting anything else comes across to me as sectarian, arrogant, and a little bit lazy.  Circulating a pamphlet like this one that is abstract when it''s convenient isn''t going to bust any cages--we need to engage in these hard questions and then organize around them.  \r\n\r\nThose of us committed to liberation continue to wrestle with these same questions about reform and revolution that you raise, but my answer and my strategy, at least for now and in this workplace, has been to organize around demands that are less than ideal but that, as Ariel says, allow us to "learn to work together, fight, and gain confidence in our own abilities" as we hopefully begin to destabilize "the capitalist rhetoric that budget cuts are inevitable and that managers know best."  This may not be the best strategy, or our tactics around May 3 may be off.  Like many of my comrades, I am open to critique because I care about building something powerful enough to topple the bosses and the rulers for good, and I don''t pretend to know with certainty what that will look like.  But I''m for engaging in a serious and sustained discussion in the spirit of building something better, not one-upping each other as "more radical" over the internet.  \r\n\r\nIf this was intended to provoke conversation or reshape organizing, why isn''t that conversation or organizing happening?  If this piece inspires you, what exactly does it inspire you to do? \r\nCan we please talk about this?', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (X11; U; Linux i686; en-US) AppleWebKit/533.4 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/5.0.375.29 Safari/533.4', '', 0, 0),
