(1898, 856, 'worldhistory', 'worldhistory@riseup.net', 'http://www.worldhistoryband.com', '71.22.136.55', '2010-04-09 23:03:14', '2010-04-10 07:03:14', 'I have never had the idea that "DIY" was a violent or non-violent movement &amp; I don''t see any reason to label it either way.  In your definition of the DIY movement, were you trying to define the entire movement, or simply what SeattleDIY is all about?  If you''re trying to define the entire DIY movement as non-violent, that just really doesn''t seem true at all, as it definitely involves an extremely broad community. If "the anarchists" (as was signed at the end of the pamphlet) feel as if they are a part of the DIY community AND they also think that violence may be necessary to work toward creating something better, I really think that''s completely valid.  The statement, "we will not be coopted by a very small portion of this community", hit me kind of hard.  "Coopted" just doesn''t seem like an appropriate word at all, as I don''t see how anyone who is part of the community can coopt the community.  And, even if it''s true that a very small portion of us agree with violence (which I''m not sure if that''s true), I really don''t think that should make a difference as to whether they are part of the community.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', 0, 272),
(1901, 856, 'Tsar', 'parkranger@gmail.com', '', '67.170.107.28', '2010-04-10 12:03:00', '2010-04-10 20:03:00', 'I wasn''t at the march, and I only briefly saw a copy of the pamphlet in question... While I feel weird about addressing this on the internets, I also think it''s important to have these kinds of conversations in a public forum. \r\n\r\nI understand wanting to dissociate the SeattleDIY website from a pamphlet that mentions shooting back at cops, especially when this site isn''t exactly secure, and it could bring undue surveillance. At the same time, I find this post to be condescending and divisionist, while speaking for the entire "DIY movement" and the entire SeattleDIY "collective". \r\n\r\nAt least three separate posts in the last couple of weeks have been made here on SDIY about events/talks regarding police brutality, state violence, and the prison industrial system. It doesn''t seem so weird to me, then, that this blog would be considered a resource for learning more about state violence and connecting with a community that opposes said violence (whatever form that opposition takes, well, that isn''t up to us to determine).\r\n\r\nClaiming that the DIY movement is about creativity and not destruction asserts another false dichotomy that I find really important to re-think. There''s a fine line - indistinguishable, I would argue - between the ideas of creativity and destruction, and to me, DIY is about make that line even more confusing. However, it''s not really useful to get into a big theoretical discussion here. \r\n\r\nI have to agree with worldhistory - how is a pamphlet suggesting SDIY as a resource "co-opting" the movement? Simply because the pamphlet doesn''t fit within your pre-determined DIY boundaries? While you state that, "Our ideals and values are not monolithic, and should not be conveyed as though they are," you''re actually reinforcing the monolith by announcing on a personal pulpit what is and isn''t part of the DIY movement. Instead of opening up discussion in the community on what might be considered DIY, you''re setting the boundaries.  \r\n\r\nI also really resent you saying that "I hope none of what I’ve written here disappoints any <b>fans</b> of the DIY movement." Really? Fans? That''s all we are? For a "collective" that claims to support creators and participators of culture, that''s a pretty rude way to relegate anyone but yourself as merely a "fan". \r\n\r\nThis is not the kind of DIY movement I want any part in.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X Mach-O; en-US; rv:1.8.1.20) Gecko/20081217 Firefox/2.0.0.20', '', 0, 0),
(1902, 856, 'Erica', 'punkrock84@gmail.com', '', '174.24.184.42', '2010-04-10 12:39:01', '2010-04-10 20:39:01', 'While I disagree with some of your statements that describe the DIY community in general (for example, I do not think that the flyer citing SeattleDIY coopts SeattleDIY or the DIY movement), I do understand and agree with your statement that the SeattleDIY website should not be taken as a supporter of or source of information about violent resistance.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3', '', 0, 0),
