(1926, 887, 'river', 'grimm@riseup.net', 'http://arcticcirclecollective.info/', '216.231.36.191', '2010-04-12 11:00:37', '2010-04-12 19:00:37', 'I feel the same as worldhistory.\r\n\r\nI feel like the people that I know, who felt attacked by Benji''s comments, are completely open to in-person dialogue and discussion.  Unfortunately, this was not an option made available to I or anyone I know before Benji made his post.\r\n\r\nAs far as I know Benji did not even approach anyone passing out "Some People Shoot Back" on Friday to engage in dialogue over his concerns.  Rather, a very public and very upsetting blog post was made.\r\n\r\nMany people felt incredibly outraged and betrayed by said blog post, and I feel like a public denunciation and analysis of his complete LACK of solidarity with those involved with the rally was appropriate, and necessary.\r\n\r\nI feel like it was appropriate and necessary to make public counterpoints to Benji''s comments not only because Benji and the SeattleDIY website are such large figureheads in the local community, but also because Benji''s comments reflect the ideas and ways of thinking of majority of the populace.  I feel like the more opportunities we have to publicly deconstruct these ways of thinking, the better.\r\n\r\nIn regards to security culture, I feel like having a public discourse on anarchist thoughts and ideas is valid, and necessary, and we need it now more than ever.  Governmental oppression is increasing, just as public outcry against institutions such as the police and FBI is also on the rise, and I don''t feel like it''s a coincidence.  \r\n\r\nI feel like anarchists need to have a public face, and have their thoughts and ideas made pubic so that the general population knows of at least one more person they can go to for resources, support, and solidarity against their own oppression.\r\n\r\nFor those that want to know more about good security culture practices when on the computer I totally recommend riseup.net''s <a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;ct=res&amp;cd=1&amp;ved=0CAYQFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fzine.riseup.net%2Fassets%2Fdigital_security_for_activists.pdf&amp;ei=BW3DS_u4JpCqswPD_tR8&amp;usg=AFQjCNFECyNMMea8flYzRLoQnhZ4gsqpXA" rel="nofollow">Digital Security for Activists</a>.\r\n\r\nThe Arctic Circle Collective will also be holding a workshop on practicing good security culture in the very near future, and it will cover the use of technology as well.\r\n\r\nriver', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (X11; U; Linux i686; en-US; rv:1.9.0.19) Gecko/2010040116 Ubuntu/9.04 (jaunty) Firefox/3.0.19', '', 0, 0),
(1931, 887, 'PM', 'nope@hotmail.com', '', '174.24.175.250', '2010-04-12 13:40:20', '2010-04-12 21:40:20', 'Echoing the other three commenters'' above sentiments, I want to say that yes, the internet is notorious for fostering ill-will, and that an open discussion in person (with good security culture) would be the best way to proceed, but also that the response (the intelligent, thoughtful response--not "reaction") to Benji has been healthy and appropriate, and that I have doubts he would have rethought or retracted his harmful comments without people calling him out on them.\r\n\r\nworldhistory says it well: "Benji’s response was quick, brutal, &amp; extremely public."  "Undoing It Ourselves" is a collaborative piece by the Arctic Circle Collective generated from conversations and signed as a group in agreement, but right now I speak only for myself.  I acknowledge that the piece is harsh and unapologetic--but only because we were defending many people, some of whom are very vulnerable right now, from very unfair, harmful, and visible attacks and misrepresentations that Benji made online--that is, publicly.  \r\n\r\nAnyone who wonders why so many sharp words have been thrown around in the internet arena over the last few days should think: who brought it here first?  I am of course for breaking down walls more than burning bridges, but who struck the match?  I see no need for leniency when defending our friends from the kinds of things Benji posted.\r\n\r\nThat said, I am encouraged by his retraction and hope dialogue continues.\r\n\r\nriver mentions Arctic Circle organizing a future workshop on security culture--an excellent idea.  I would also like to add that I am going to look into making some calls to PDX for folks interested in coming here to discuss General Assemblies and how they can be used to discuss strategies, tactics, and goals for actions.  Meanwhile, if anyone wants to organize an open, face-to-face dialogue, on any scale, about the action and its aftermath, I would love to participate, but I doubt I''ll be willing to continue discussion online.  To be honest, I am somewhat embarrassed to have spent this much time on this already when there are so many other things that demand our attention: (legal support, fund raising, keeping a momentum, analysis, etc.)  Unfortunately, this was necessary.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', 0, 0),
(1932, 887, 'Benji', 'heartxmurmur@yahoo.com', 'http://', '24.17.221.250', '2010-04-12 14:47:39', '2010-04-12 22:47:39', 'PM, the problem with what has happened here is echoed in how you''re responding. First - I would have ABSOLUTELY responded well to direct communication. Using the bully pulpit to silence my criticism didn''t just lead to me retracting my statement, but has left me feeling isolated, personally attacked, and and disregarded. Second, the "who struck the match" argument is a terrible justification for attacking someone personally and with such fervor. My criticisms were about how things went down and very specific particulars - not any judgments of the nature or quality of the people who partook in the actions. \r\nThough I abused my privilege and use of this space in the criticism of the tactics employed in the protest, there are significant reasons I felt like I needed to distance myself and seattlediy from the more aggressive elements of the protest (and the pamphlet) immediately. \r\nI''m earnestly sorry for the original tone and some serious mistakes I made in representing both myself and the collective in that original hurried and poorly worded blog post. Still, I don''t see how my mistakes (which I tried to remedy quickly) warranted the kind of venom and vitriol that came my way, and so publicly, especially as a statement made by an entire collective of people whom I highly regard and think of warmly. I look forward to having a good-faith discussion in person about these things.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.6; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3', '', 0, 1),
