ation above doesn''t make sense, have a look at Matt Cutt''s video explanation:<br\n/><p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/prevent-site-being-indexed/"><em>Click here to view the embedded video.</em></a></p></p><p>So, if you want to effectively hide pages from the search engines, and this might seem contradictory, you <em>need</em> them to index those pages. Why? Because when they index those pages, you can tell them not to List them. There''s two ways of doing that: by using robots meta tags, like this (and I''ve got an article on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/articles/robots-meta-tags/">robots meta tags</a> that''s more extensive):</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="html" style="font-family:monospace;">&lt;meta name=&quot;robots&quot; content=&quot;noindex,nofollow&quot;/&gt;</pre></div></div><p>The issue with a tag like that is that you have to add it to each and every page. That''s why the search engines came up with the <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/x-robots-tag-play/">X-Robots-Tag HTTP header</a>. This allows you to specify an HTTP header called <code>X-Robots-Tag</code>, and set the value as you would the meta robots tags value. The cool thing about this is that you can do it for an entire site. So, if your site is running on Apache, and mod_headers is enabled (it usually is), you could add the following single line to your <em>.htaccess</em> file:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="apache" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #00007f;">Header</span> set X-Robots-Tag <span style="color: #7f007f;">&quot;noindex, nofollow&quot;</span></pre></div></div><p>And it''d have the effect that that entire site <em>can</em> be indexed, but will never be shown in the search results. So, get rid of that robots.txt file with <code>Disallow: /</code> in it, and use the X-Robots-Tag instead!</p><p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/prevent-site-being-indexed/">Preventing your site from being indexed, the right way</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> <img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/7cHSZ2f5VEM" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:5;a:15:{s:5:"title";s:24:"Rankings that make sense";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/joostdevalk/~3/Vh2qb3Fey3U/";s:8:"comments";s:51:"http://yoast.com/rankings-that-make-sense/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Mon, 07 Dec 2009 14:20:50 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Joost de Valk";}s:8:"category";s:45:"AnalyticsSEOGoogle AnalyticsRankingsSEO tools";s:4:"guid";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=1873";s:11:"description";s:741:"We''ve written about rankings here before, for instance: how to track them with Google Analytics, part I and part II and even why they are worthless (the latter post by Eduard, who has, starting december 1st, joined us at OrangeValley!!), on top of that, I was using this rank tracker all the time!\nBut today, I [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/rankings-that-make-sense/">Rankings that make sense</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:7:"content";s:13:"Array        ";s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:47:"http://yoast.com/rankings-that-make-sense/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"31";}s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:4:"    ";s:13:"content_title";s:76:"seo-rank-monitor-logoSEO Ranking Monitorkeyword-rankingstag-keyword-rankings";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:110:"http://yoast.com/rankings-t