ent";s:1:" ";s:13:"content_title";s:13:"compatibility";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:146:"http://yoast.com/plugin-compatibility-data-now-crowdsourced/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=plugin-compatibility-data-now-crowdsourced";}s:7:"summary";s:761:"One of the things Mark Jaquith and I talked about when Mark was on Press This a month back, in the episode aptly titled the Future of WordPress, was that Automattic would be adding a way for people to indicate whether a certain plugin was working for them or not, regardless of what the plugins [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/plugin-compatibility-data-now-crowdsourced/">Plugin Compatibility data now crowdsourced</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:12:"atom_content";s:1:"A";}i:17;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:45:"Quick WP tip #2: Conditional Thickbox loading";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/joostdevalk/~3/-RWC82s6ZZw/";s:8:"comments";s:55:"http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 14 Oct 2009 20:19:27 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Joost de Valk";}s:8:"category";s:25:"WordPressWordPress Themes";s:4:"guid";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=1621";s:11:"description";s:737:"Another quick tip to help you optimize your site: sometimes you want to load one or more images in a post in a nice Thickbox or Lightbox. But in most cases, you don''t need to load these scripts, wouldn''t it be cool if you could load these scripts only when you want them to load?\nI [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/">Quick WP tip #2: Conditional Thickbox loading</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:4493:"<p>Another quick tip to help you optimize your site: sometimes you want to load one or more images in a post in a nice <a\nhref="http://jquery.com/demo/thickbox/">Thickbox</a> or <a\nhref="http://www.huddletogether.com/projects/lightbox2/">Lightbox</a>. But in most cases, you don''t need to load these scripts, wouldn''t it be cool if you could load these scripts <em>only when you want them to load</em>?</p><p>I decided, that the only time I want Thickbox to load, is when I manually add <code>class="thickbox"</code> to the code of a post or page. So I wrote up a little script that checks for that, and loads Thickbox if needed. Now you need to know that to make Thickbox work, you need to load both a script and a css file, so the complete code is the following:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">function</span> yst_conditional_thickbox<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span>\n  <span style="color: #990000;">global</span> <span style="color: #000088;">$post</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n  <span style="color: #b1b100;">if</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span>is_singular<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">&amp;&amp;</span> \n    <span style="color: #990000;">strpos</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #000088;">$post</span><span style="color: #339933;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #004000;">post_content</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''class=&quot;thickbox&quot;''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">!==</span> <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">false</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span>\n      wp_enqueue_script<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''thickbox''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n      wp_enqueue_style<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''thickbox''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n  <span style="color: #009900;">&#125;</span>\n<span style="color: #009900;">&#125;</span>\nadd_action<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''wp_print_styles''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''yst_conditional_thickbox''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span></pre></div></div><p>This code should go into your themes <em>functions.php</em> file. Let''s explain it a bit: the function checks whether the content of the post contains the text <code>class="thickbox"</code>. If it finds this text, it enqueues both the Thickbox script and CSS file. The <code>add_action</code> "hooks" this function to a WordPress hook. I use the <code>wp_print_styles</code> hook here, because that executes in the head, and makes sure both the stylesheet and the script file get loaded properly.</p><p>Now of course there''s nicer ways of doing this, like making it into a full regex to see if class="thickbox" is actually set on a link, to prevent it from loading on a post like this one, which doesn''t have a thickboxed image in it, but does contain the text. But let''s be honest, how often is that really the case? This simple conditional load means you can use Thickbox when you need it, but you''re not making your users download Thickbox all the time when you''re only using it in 5% of your posts.</p><p>Let me know in the comments if this works for you, and which other things you think you should load conditionally, to make your blog a bit faster and more userfriendly!</p><p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/">Quick WP tip #2: Conditional Thickbox loading</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> <img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/-RWC82s6ZZw" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:51:"http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"30";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:118:"http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=conditional-thickbox-loading";}s:7:"summary";s:737:"Another quick tip to help you optimize your site: sometimes you want to load one or more images in a post in a nice Thickbox or Lightbox. But in most cases, you don''t need to load these scripts, wouldn''t it be cool if you could load these scripts only when you want them to load?\nI [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/">Quick WP tip #2: Conditional Thickbox loading</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:12:"atom_content";s:4493:"<p>Another quick tip to help you optimize your site: sometimes you want to load one or more images in a post in a nice <a\nhref="http://jquery.com/demo/thickbox/">Thickbox</a> or <a\nhref="http://www.huddletogether.com/projects/lightbox2/">Lightbox</a>. But in most cases, you don''t need to load these scripts, wouldn''t it be cool if you could load these scripts <em>only when you want them to load</em>?</p><p>I decided, that the only time I want Thickbox to load, is when I manually add <code>class="thickbox"</code> to the code of a post or page. So I wrote up a little script that checks for that, and loads Thickbox if needed. Now you need to know that to make Thickbox work, you need to load both a script and a css file, so the complete code is the following:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">function</span> yst_conditional_thickbox<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span>\n  <span style="color: #990000;">global</span> <span style="color: #000088;">$post</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n  <span style="color: #b1b100;">if</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span>is_singular<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">&amp;&amp;</span> \n    <span style="color: #990000;">strpos</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #000088;">$post</span><span style="color: #339933;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #004000;">post_content</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''class=&quot;thickbox&quot;''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">!==</span> <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">false</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span>\n      wp_enqueue_script<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''thickbox''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n      wp_enqueue_style<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''thickbox''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span>\n  <span style="color: #009900;">&#125;</span>\n<span style="color: #009900;">&#125;</span>\nadd_action<span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''wp_print_styles''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span><span style="color: #0000ff;">''yst_conditional_thickbox''</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span><span style="color: #339933;">;</span></pre></div></div><p>This code should go into your themes <em>functions.php</em> file. Let''s explain it a bit: the function checks whether the content of the post contains the text <code>class="thickbox"</code>. If it finds this text, it enqueues both the Thickbox script and CSS file. The <code>add_action</code> "hooks" this function to a WordPress hook. I use the <code>wp_print_styles</code> hook here, because that executes in the head, and makes sure both the stylesheet and the script file get loaded properly.</p><p>Now of course there''s nicer ways of doing this, like making it into a full regex to see if class="thickbox" is actually set on a link, to prevent it from loading on a post like this one, which doesn''t have a thickboxed image in it, but does contain the text. But let''s be honest, how often is that really the case? This simple conditional load means you can use Thickbox when you need it, but you''re not making your users download Thickbox all the time when you''re only using it in 5% of your posts.</p><p>Let me know in the comments if this works for you, and which other things you think you should load conditionally, to make your blog a bit faster and more userfriendly!</p><p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/conditional-thickbox-loading/">Quick WP tip #2: Conditional Thickbox loading</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> <img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/-RWC82s6ZZw" height="1" width="1"/>";}i:18;a:15:{s:5:"title";s:21:"WordPress Debug Theme";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/joostdevalk/~3/0Ja0QTjxcX8/";s:8:"comments";s:48:"http://yoast.com/wordpress-debug-theme/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 14 Oct 2009 13:14:08 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Joost de Valk";}s:8:"category";s:42:"WordPressWordPress PluginsWordPress Themes";s:4:"guid";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=1618";s:11:"description";s:713:"Warning: major geekery ahead! Sometimes you need to see what''s wrong with a WordPress install, and you need to see it fast. I''ve had a set of hacks around for a while to do that, but finally started combining it into a WordPress Debug Theme. This theme is quite simple for now, as it only [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-debug-theme/">WordPress Debug Theme</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:7:"content";s:7:"Array  ";s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:44:"http://yoast.com/wordpress-debug-theme/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"61";}s:5:"media";a:2:{s:7:"content";s:1:" ";s:13:"content_title";s:17:"Yoast Debug Theme";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:104:"http://yoast.com/wordpress-debug-theme/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=wordpress-debug-theme";}s:7:"summary";s:713:"Warning: major geekery ahead! Sometimes you need to see what''s wrong with a WordPress install, and you need to see it fast. I''ve had a set of hacks around for a while to do that, but finally started combining it into a WordPress Debug Theme. This theme is quite simple for now, as it only [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-debug-theme/">WordPress Debug Theme</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:12:"atom_content";s:1:"A";}i:19;a:14:{s:5:"title";s:34:"Upgrading issues with WordPress MU";s:4:"link";s:58:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/joostdevalk/~3/WZKgq0mMGqI/";s:8:"comments";s:61:"http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Tue, 13 Oct 2009 20:30:56 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:13:"Joost de Valk";}s:8:"category";s:21:"WordPressWordPress Mu";s:4:"guid";s:24:"http://yoast.com/?p=1617";s:11:"description";s:775:"I was upgrading a WordPress MU site we work on and came across an annoying issue: core update wouldn''t work the way it''s supposed to. I got the following error:\nUnpacking the update.\nCould not copy files.\nInstallation Failed.\nAfter a bit of Googling I found a thread in the WordPress forums that contained a gem of a fix:\nIn [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/">Upgrading issues with WordPress MU</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:3358:"<p>I was upgrading a WordPress MU site we work on and came across an annoying issue: core update wouldn''t work the way it''s supposed to. I got the following error:</p><pre>Unpacking the update.\nCould not copy files.\nInstallation Failed.</pre><p>After a bit of Googling I found a thread in the WordPress forums that contained a <a\nhref="http://mu.wordpress.org/forums/topic/13506#post-79964" rel="nofollow">gem of a fix</a>:</p><p>In the file <em>/wp-admin/includes/class-wp-upgrader.php</em> change this:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #666666; font-style: italic;">// Copy update-core.php from the new version into place.</span>\n<span style="color: #b1b100;">if</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">!</span><span style="color: #000088;">$wp_filesystem</span><span style="color: #339933;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #004000;">copy</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #000088;">$working_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''/wordpress/wp-admin/includes/\n  update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #000088;">$wp_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''wp-admin/includes/update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> \n  <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">true</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span></pre></div></div><p>To:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #666666; font-style: italic;">// Copy update-core.php from the new version into place.</span>\n<span style="color: #b1b100;">if</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">!</span><span style="color: #000088;">$wp_filesystem</span><span style="color: #339933;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #004000;">copy</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #000088;">$working_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''/wordpress-mu/wp-admin/includes/\n  update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #000088;">$wp_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''wp-admin/includes/update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> \n  <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">true</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span></pre></div></div><p>And low and behold: my automatic upgrade worked at once.</p><p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/">Upgrading issues with WordPress MU</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> <img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/WZKgq0mMGqI" height="1" width="1"/>";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:57:"http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/feed/";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:2:"14";}s:10:"feedburner";a:1:{s:8:"origlink";s:130:"http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/#utm_source=rss&utm_medium=rss&utm_campaign=upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu";}s:7:"summary";s:775:"I was upgrading a WordPress MU site we work on and came across an annoying issue: core update wouldn''t work the way it''s supposed to. I got the following error:\nUnpacking the update.\nCould not copy files.\nInstallation Failed.\nAfter a bit of Googling I found a thread in the WordPress forums that contained a gem of a fix:\nIn [...]<p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/">Upgrading issues with WordPress MU</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> ";s:12:"atom_content";s:3358:"<p>I was upgrading a WordPress MU site we work on and came across an annoying issue: core update wouldn''t work the way it''s supposed to. I got the following error:</p><pre>Unpacking the update.\nCould not copy files.\nInstallation Failed.</pre><p>After a bit of Googling I found a thread in the WordPress forums that contained a <a\nhref="http://mu.wordpress.org/forums/topic/13506#post-79964" rel="nofollow">gem of a fix</a>:</p><p>In the file <em>/wp-admin/includes/class-wp-upgrader.php</em> change this:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #666666; font-style: italic;">// Copy update-core.php from the new version into place.</span>\n<span style="color: #b1b100;">if</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">!</span><span style="color: #000088;">$wp_filesystem</span><span style="color: #339933;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #004000;">copy</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #000088;">$working_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''/wordpress/wp-admin/includes/\n  update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #000088;">$wp_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''wp-admin/includes/update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> \n  <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">true</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span></pre></div></div><p>To:</p><div\nclass="wp_syntax"><div\nclass="code"><pre class="php" style="font-family:monospace;"><span style="color: #666666; font-style: italic;">// Copy update-core.php from the new version into place.</span>\n<span style="color: #b1b100;">if</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span> <span style="color: #339933;">!</span><span style="color: #000088;">$wp_filesystem</span><span style="color: #339933;">-&gt;</span><span style="color: #004000;">copy</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#40;</span><span style="color: #000088;">$working_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''/wordpress-mu/wp-admin/includes/\n  update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> <span style="color: #000088;">$wp_dir</span> <span style="color: #339933;">.</span> <span style="color: #0000ff;">''wp-admin/includes/update-core.php''</span><span style="color: #339933;">,</span> \n  <span style="color: #000000; font-weight: bold;">true</span><span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#41;</span> <span style="color: #009900;">&#123;</span></pre></div></div><p>And low and behold: my automatic upgrade worked at once.</p><p><a\nhref="http://yoast.com/upgrading-issues-with-wordpress-mu/">Upgrading issues with WordPress MU</a> is a post from <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/about-me/">Joost de Valk</a>&#39;s <a\nhref="http://yoast.com">Yoast - Tweaking Websites</a>.A good WordPress blog needs good hosting, you don''t want your blog to be slow, or, even worse, down, do you? Check out my thoughts on <a\nhref="http://yoast.com/wordpress-hosting/">WordPress hosting</a>!</p> <img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/joostdevalk/~4/WZKgq0mMGqI" height="1" width="1"/>";}}s