(376, 11, '2009-07-06 21:10:51', '2009-07-07 05:10:51', 'On Saturday June 27 some people organized a guerilla dance party in the parking lot of a now torn-down queer bar. They were tired of paying 15 dollars to get into a 21+beer garden during a weekend of corporate-sponsored pride. The cops came quick, hitting a woman with a flashlight, wrongly arresting one man and physically harassing a large group of revelers. What did the cops have to say to the queers who just wanted to dance for free? "Listen the reason that woman was hit is because were all over-worked. A good example is RODNEY KING. Those were good guys, just overworked." Jail and court support may be needed. The community will keep you posted.\r\n\r\nSome folks have begun organizing a Radical Lending Library and/or Infoshop. Meetings have just begun and you can catch up with them on Thursday, July 2 at 7pm at The Bikery. You can also email seattle_infoshop@lists.riseup.net for more details about how to get involved.\r\n\r\nPilot Books is a new independent book store in Capitol Hill, located upstairs at 219 Broadway, between Olive and Thomas. They carry small press and local authors. Also there is a really cool lending library upstairs. Starting this month, Pilot Books will host weekly writers workshops. Each will have a distinct theme - like lyric poetry, stream of consciousness prose, or abstract minimalism - so you can drop in for styles you like and politely avoid the ones you don’t. You can get more info about that and other events listen in their online calendar at <a href="http://pilotbooksseattle.com/wordpress">pilotbooksseattle.com/wordpress</a>.\r\n\r\nThere is also a new book club starting! Details yet to be determined – check SeattleDIY.com for more info, or to suggest any of the above!\r\n\r\nAs some of you may have noticed, Chiladelphia is no longer doing house shows. That sweaty basement holds many good memories – RIP ChillyD!\r\n\r\nThere is a new space called “The Morgue” doing shows in Gorgetown. They also seem to be hosting pyrate punx open meetings.\r\n\r\nIn other venue closings, the Holy Mountain has shuttered their doors. Possible renaming and/or re-creation in the works, so stay tuned for shows at the Black Lodge.\r\n\r\nNow is prime time for fresh produce, so remember to go to your local farmer''s market. They all take food stamps (just ask at the info tables set up, sometimes you have to buy tokens to use at the stands)! Check out the times and locations listed on the back page.\r\n\r\nCome to the Arctic Circle on Friday, July 10th for a secret cafe to benefit the AETA 4! There will be delicious food, delectable company, and secret entertainment. Admission will be sliding scale ($1-10), and dinner starts promptly at 5:30. Who are the AETA 4? Nathan Pope, Adriana Stumpo, Joseph Buddenberg, and Maryam Khajavi were arrested in February of 2009 for public protest, and charged by the FBI for violating the Animal Enterprise Terrorism Act. The AETA 4 face an absurd maximum of ten years in prison for simply writing in chalk on the sidewalk of UCSC, wearing bandanas while protesting, and distributing flyers about animal research.\r\n    \r\nThe AETA (Animal Enterprise Terrorism Act) strip activists of First Amendment rights and is a part of a larger movement directed by the FBI that many environmental activists refer to as the “Green Scare” (http://greenscare.org), which is being used to crack down on environmental and animal rights organizing and actions, creating a culture of fear in activist communities in order to uphold corporate “rights” to profit. It is crucial to work at establishing a viable and supportive community that not only refuses to be silenced and intimidated, but reaches out to those being persecuted for the sake of profits. So, come join us if you can, and please bring money to benefit the AETA 4. For more information visit: <a href="http://www.aeta4.org">www.aeta4.org</a>\r\n\r\nAlso check out SeattleDIY.com, and read/contribute to our new blog! That''s what you are reading right now.', 'July News', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'july-news', '', '', '2009-07-06 21:10:51', '2009-07-07 05:10:51', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=376', 0, 'post', '', 0),
