(464, 98, '2009-08-17 15:16:05', '2009-08-17 23:16:05', '<p style="text-align: center"><img class="aligncenter" src="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3064/2798485245_15a0d356e2.jpg" alt="Carousel Fest 2008 Love!" width="500" height="375" /></p>\n\n<p>Hey Everybody!</p>\n\n<p>Something wonderful is about to happen. It has nothing to do with <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Odyssey_Two" target="_blank"><em>2010 a Space Odyssey</em></a> (even though that would be <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jupiter" target="_blank">totally cool</a>!) but it has to do with <em>2009 a Seattle Odyssey</em>.</p>\n\n<p>Carousel Fest 2009!</p>\n\n<p>And we need volunteers to help with whatever they can for the three days and six spaces that it will be taking place. As we have only two weeks left until the festival begins, we''re pressed to have individuals committed to helping out on this.</p>\n\n<p>All proceeds this year go to the <a href="http://www.urbanreststop.org/" target="_blank">Urban Rest Stop</a> and <a href="http://www.hollowearthradio.com/" target="_blank">Hollow Earth Radio</a> so even if you are unsure or unable to volunteer for Carousel Fest this year, you can still come, see amazing musical acts, and help out two amazing organizations. For more updated information about the festival itself, visit Carousel Festival''s MySpace: <a href="http://www.myspace.com/carouselfestival" target="_blank">http://www.myspace.com/carouselfestival</a></p>\n\n<p>If you are interested in volunteering or have any questions about it, feel fine to e-mail me: <strong>kenneth.​m.​piekarski@​gmail.​com</strong></p>\n\n<p>With Much Love (I mean it),</p>\n\n<p>-Kenneth-</p>', 'Carousel Festival Volunteering', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '455-autosave', '', '', '2009-08-17 15:16:05', '2009-08-17 23:16:05', '', 455, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=464', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(465, 1, '2009-08-14 12:40:23', '2009-08-14 20:40:23', '<img src="http://seattlediy.com/images/zinerelease.jpg" alt="zine release party" width="550"/>\r\n\r\nThe SeattleDIY Collective has been working on a zine with some other fine folks which will be a listing of places and projects in town that people can become engaged in, and have it be a guide to the city that isn''t just a list of cool places to go, but places where you can become an active participant. All sorts of places like The Bikery and projects like Food Not Bombs will be described, with information about how you can check them out and get more involved. The cover is beautifully silk screened, and there will be a pull-out insert poster with a list of all sorts of great stuff going on. \r\n\r\nThe zine release party will be on August 16th at The Vera Project at 6pm, and for $5 entry you''ll get a copy of the zine and some amazingly delicious vegan food cooked by none other than The Asian Cajun (TM!), and music spun by Hollow Earth Radio DJ David Newman. You should definitely come and hang out with other exciting people who share similar passions and who do cool stuff, or if you''re part of a project you can come and bring info to give to peeps. For more info, email us at sdiycollective@gmail.com!\r\n', 'DIY Directory zine release party!', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '430-revision-7', '', '', '2009-08-14 12:40:23', '2009-08-14 20:40:23', '', 430, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=465', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(512, 1, '2009-09-21 12:15:26', '2009-09-21 20:15:26', '<p>An energized cooperative movement has thrust the co-op business model into the spotlight, prompting interest in why this centuries-old way of need-meeting is experiencing a renaissance. In support of next-wave cooperative enterprise, October 3 at Richard Hugo House, <a href="http://www.madisonmarket.coop/" target="_self">Central Co-op</a> and the <a href="http://www.balleseattle.org/" target="_self">Business Alliance for Local Living Economies </a>(BALLE) Seattle will host Strengthening Local Independent Co-ops Everywhere (<a href="http://www.madisonmarket.com/uploads/slice-poster.pdf" target="_self">SLICE)</a>, a day-long workshop on cooperative basics for nascent and existing co-ops and folks who want to buff up their co-op engagement.<br />\n<br />\nWith the region’s best and brightest co-op mentors, participants will gain an understanding of how to start a cooperative, best practices, nitty-gritty details, and inspiration. The highly interactive program will address different co-op models and how to get incorporated; assessing needs and creating community tools to fulfill them; team structure and development; global cooperation; generating capital and equity; and coalition building.<br />\n<br />\nIn addition to a comprehensive workshop schedule and the chance to network with other cooperators, SLICE goers will enjoy coffee and tea, compliments of Equal Exchange co-op, breakfast and lunch catered by Central Co-op, and beer, courtesy of worker-owned Full Sail Brewery. Visit <a href="http://www.madisonmarket.coop/" target="_self">madisonmarket.coop</a> to learn more, purchase your $30 ticket, sign-up for work-trade, or apply for one of 13 scholarships, made possible by Seattle Metropolitan Credit Union and Group Health Credit Union.</p>\n\nworkshop on October 3rd @ ', 'SLICE, A Day-Long Workshop About How to Start Your Own Co-op', 0, 'SLICE: Strengthening Local Independent Co-ops Everywhere is a day-long workshop on cooperative basics for nascent and existing co-ops and folks who want to buff up their co-op engagement.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '501-autosave', '', '', '2009-09-21 12:15:26', '2009-09-21 20:15:26', '', 501, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=512', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(511, 1, '2009-09-17 14:37:03', '2009-09-17 22:37:03', '<p>An energized cooperative movement has thrust the co-op business model into the spotlight, prompting interest in why this centuries-old way of need-meeting is experiencing a renaissance. In support of next-wave cooperative enterprise, October 3 at Richard Hugo House, <a href="http://www.madisonmarket.coop/" target="_self">Central Co-op</a> and the <a href="http://www.balleseattle.org/" target="_self">Business Alliance for Local Living Economies </a>(BALLE) Seattle will host Strengthening Local Independent Co-ops Everywhere (<a href="http://www.madisonmarket.com/uploads/slice-poster.pdf" target="_self">SLICE)</a>, a day-long workshop on cooperative basics for nascent and existing co-ops and folks who want to buff up their co-op engagement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith the region’s best and brightest co-op mentors, participants will gain an understanding of how to start a cooperative, best practices, nitty-gritty details, and inspiration. The highly interactive program will address different co-op models and how to get incorporated; assessing needs and creating community tools to fulfill them; team structure and development; global cooperation; generating capital and equity; and coalition building.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn addition to a comprehensive workshop schedule and the chance to network with other cooperators, SLICE goers will enjoy coffee and tea, compliments of Equal Exchange co-op, breakfast and lunch catered by Central Co-op, and beer, courtesy of worker-owned Full Sail Brewery. Visit <a href="http://www.madisonmarket.coop/" target="_self">madisonmarket.coop</a> to learn more, purchase your $30 ticket, sign-up for work-trade, or apply for one of 13 scholarships, made possible by Seattle Metropolitan Credit Union and Group Health Credit Union.</p>', 'SLICE, A Day-Long Workshop About How to Start Your Own Co-op', 0, 'SLICE: Strengthening Local Independent Co-ops Everywhere is a day-long workshop on cooperative basics for nascent and existing co-ops and folks who want to buff up their co-op engagement.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '501-revision-3', '', '', '2009-09-17 14:37:03', '2009-09-17 22:37:03', '', 501, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=511', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
