(471, 99, '2009-08-17 22:02:54', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Please join us this Friday, August 21st for food, discussion, literature, and music to benefit the Tarnac 9.  The Tarnac 9 are facing terrorism charges in France and have been accused of authoring <em>The Coming Insurrection</em>.\n\n<strong>Who are the Tarnac 9?</strong>\n\nOn November 11th 2008, French Anti-Terrorism Police arrested around twenty people, mostly in Tarnac, a small village in the Corrèze region of central France.  Nine were subsequently accused of “criminal association for the purposes of terrorist activity” in connection with the sabotage of train lines which had caused delays on the French railways. Very little evidence has been presented against them, but central to the prosecution is their alleged authorship of a book, <em>The Coming Insurrection,</em> and their association with what a scare-mongering French government and media have termed an “ultra-left” or “anarcho-autonomous movement”.\n\nThey and others are the victims of a witch-hunt in which the word “terrorism” is applied to any ideas and practices which challenge the status quo--much like the U.S. government''s Green Scare. An international movement is emerging in their support.\n\n<strong>What is <em>The Coming Insurrection?</em></strong>\n\nIt''s important to note that the Tarnac 9 have maintained they are <em>not</em> the authors of <em>The Coming Insurrection</em>, which was penned by the anonymous group The Invisible Committee.  That said, the booklet claims that recent financial crisis, civil unrest and environmental degradation stem from capitalism. According to the authors, "Thirty years of ''crisis,'' mass unemployment, and flagging growth, and they still want us to believe in the economy... We have to see that the economy is itself the crisis. It''s not that there''s not enough work, it''s that there is too much of it."\n\nThe book aims to motivate the reader to direct action, promoting a form of insurrectionary anarchism.\n\nHere''s what Fox News'' Glenn Beck has to say about it:\n\n', 'TARNAC 9 BENEFIT AT ARCTIC CIRCLE', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-08-17 22:02:54', '2009-08-18 06:02:54', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=471', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(472, 99, '2009-08-17 22:22:54', '2009-08-18 06:22:54', '<p><h1>LAST MINUTE UPDATE: Music by <a href="http://www.myspace.com/thewitchesof">the Witches Of</a> . . .</h1></p>\r\n<p>Please join us this <strong>Friday, August 21st</strong> for food, discussion, literature, and music to benefit the <a href="http://tarnac9.wordpress.com/">Tarnac 9.</a> The Tarnac 9 are facing terrorism charges in France and have been accused of authoring <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Coming_Insurrection">The Coming Insurrection</a></em>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>7 PM at <a href="http://arcticcirclehouse.info/">the Arctic Circle</a>, a house in Georgetown<br />\r\n 6633 Ellis Ave S</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Who are the Tarnac 9?</strong></p>\r\n<p>On November 11th 2008, French Anti-Terrorism Police arrested around twenty people, mostly in Tarnac, a small village in the Corrèze region of central France.  Nine were subsequently accused of “criminal association for the purposes of terrorist activity” in connection with the sabotage of train lines which had caused delays on the French railways. Very little evidence has been presented against them, but central to the prosecution is their alleged authorship of a book, <em>The Coming Insurrection,</em> and their association with what a scare-mongering French government and media have termed an “ultra-left” or “anarcho-autonomous movement”.</p>\r\n<p>They and others are the victims of a witch-hunt in which the word “terrorism” is applied to any ideas and practices which challenge the status quo--much like the U.S. government''s Green Scare. An international movement is emerging in their support.</p>\r\n<p><strong>What is <em>The Coming Insurrection?</em></strong></p>\r\n<p>It''s important to note that the Tarnac 9 have maintained they are <em>not</em> the authors of <em>The Coming Insurrection</em>, which was penned by the anonymous group The Invisible Committee.  That said, the booklet has generated a lot of excitement and is a poetic indictment of contemporary capitalist culture.  The book aims to motivate the reader to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direct_action">direct action</a>, promoting a form of <a href="http://www.insurgentdesire.org.uk/notes.htm">insurrectionary anarchism</a>.</p>\r\n<p>You can read it for <a href="http://tarnac9.wordpress.com/texts/the-coming-insurrection/">free here</a>, or picking up your own copy at the benefit from the Tout Niquer distro. (If you cannot attend but still want a print copy, they are also available at <a href="http://www.leftbankbooks.com/store/?&amp;cookieSet=1">Left Bank Books</a>.)</p>\r\n<p><strong>MUSIC TBA.</strong><a href="http://arcticcirclehouse.info/"> Let''s hang out!</a></p>\r\n', 'FRIDAY: TARNAC 9 BENEFIT AT ARCTIC CIRCLE', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'friday-tarnac-9-benefit-at-arctic-circle', '', '', '2009-08-21 11:21:22', '2009-08-21 19:21:22', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=472', 0, 'post', '', 0),
