(588, 1, '2009-12-05 15:52:34', '2009-12-05 23:52:34', '<img src="http://www.cara-seattle.org/images/ladiesfirst.jpg" width="400" alt="" />\r\nLadies First – a project of CARA\r\n(Communities Against Rape & Abuse)\r\nEvery First Saturday of the month at Hidmo \r\n\r\n8PM Open Mic / 9PM Features / all ages\r\nfree (donation)\r\n \r\n\r\nSaturday Dec 5th features:\r\nGeneiva Arunga\r\nSista Hailstorm\r\n& dj Miss Broadway\r\n \r\nPeace and Light, CARA Community.\r\n\r\nLooking for some fire and spice to set a strong year’s end?  Join us for the 2009’s final Ladies First THIS coming Saturday.  It will be a night of mind opening inspiration with features Geneiva Arunga and\r\nSista Hailstorm with dj Miss Broadway on the decks.\r\n\r\nPlease encourage sister friends to come get on the open-mic @ 8pm; or sister crafts/artists to bring their work to the open marketplace.\r\n \r\n\r\nThis Saturday’s featured artists:\r\n \r\n\r\nGeneiva Arunga is a gifted young artist, community organizer and scholar wise beyond her years. Her poetry is truthful and unapologetic utilizing art as a platform to open minds and initiate change. As a youth activist, Geneiva is involved with a number of organizations within the Seattle area. \r\nSista Hailstorm has spent much time over the past several years traveling around the world ripping up stages.  A powerful visionary and deeply rounded artist, her style and voice bring new energy to a revolutionary movement.  Her work consciously touches the restoring of balance; healing; and training the strongest physical, mental and spiritual self.\r\nDJ Miss Broadway started deejaying in the mid-90’s on pirate radio, house parties, and local fund raisers using cassette tapes and vinyl. She has been deejaying at Seattle dance clubs and bars since 2001 using vinyl, playing music of all sorts, mainly from the 1960’s – the 1990’s.  DJ Miss Broadway has the most fun spinnin’ Underground Hip Hop and Disco, though her heart is mainly with Jazz.\r\n\r\n--------------------------\r\n\r\n<img src="http://a3.twimg.com/profile_images/520868143/3_police_beat.jpg" alt="" />\r\nPoplife\r\nPop Life Community Readings\r\nKicks off THIS Sunday December 6\r\n5pm / All Ages\r\n$3\r\n_________________________\r\nOpen conversations about texts selected for the neighborhood by Charles Tonderai Mudede.\r\n \r\nFIRST SESSION: Reading from Spinoza’s Ethics: Proposition 14 to Proposition 20\r\n\r\nFind readings and session notes online .\r\nFollow @poplifereadings on Twitter for updates.\r\nCome. Participate.\r\n \r\nNEXT SESSION: The City of the Imagination\r\n5pm Sunday, Dccember 20\r\nReading “The Swan” by Charles Baudelaire \r\nWill discuss the human body, urban space, the city as memory storage, and connect all of this to the difference between biological evolution and cultural evolution.\r\n\r\n---------------------\r\n\r\n<a href=" <img src="http://origin.ih.constantcontact.com/fs006/1101970789218/img/29.jpg?a=1102859858659" alt="" />">S.O.S : Safety for Our Streets\r\n</a>Monday December 7th\r\n6:00pm to 8:00pm\r\nat Garfield Community Center\r\n(2323 East Cherry Street)\r\nopen to all ages / free\r\nchildcare & appetizers provided \r\n \r\n \r\nClothesline Project\r\n\r\nGreetings Hidmo Friends, Family, and Community Partners:\r\n \r\nWe have been steadily planning the next Hidmo Community Empowerment Project Forum and would like to invite everyone in the community to take part!\r\n \r\n \r\nSOS will be an interactive discussion designed to engage individuals in various ways about safety in the Central District. The forum will be the culmination of Hidmo CEP’s “The Central District Clothesline Project”. Historically, the Clothesline Project was a way for women to use t-shirts and a clothesline to testify about violence that happens to them and their community, or that of someone they knew. You can find out more history at http://www.clotheslineproject.org/History.html. We are expanding this concept to all residents and members of the community, and are partnering with Central District businesses, residents, churches and schools to advocate for safety, in all its forms, within our community. The anonymous T-shirts will be made at Central District community hubs all week long. To find a location to make a shirt visit www.hidmo.org or stop by Hidmo (2000 S. Jackson Street) where we will be making shirts Dec 1st – 4th from 5:30 to 7:00pm. This neighborhood-wide effort is unique in that it seeks to bring together a community stratified, and often fragmented, by our differences. The overall goal of the forum is to continue the work that we are all doing to get to know each other better, to feel safer in our neighborhood and to empower our community.\r\n \r\nFor more information or questions about the upcoming forum or the Hidmo Community Empowerment Project please contact Jason Davison at jason@hidmo.org or 206-328-7088 ', 'repost: Three days of community events at Hidmo', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'repost-three-days-of-community-events-at-hidmo', '', '', '2009-12-05 16:01:02', '2009-12-06 00:01:02', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=588', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(593, 1, '2009-12-05 16:00:04', '2009-12-06 00:00:04', '<img src="http://www.cara-seattle.org/images/ladiesfirst.jpg" alt="" />\r\nLadies First – a project of CARA\r\n(Communities Against Rape & Abuse)\r\nEvery First Saturday of the month at Hidmo \r\n\r\n8PM Open Mic / 9PM Features / all ages\r\nfree (donation)\r\n \r\n\r\nSaturday Dec 5th features:\r\nGeneiva Arunga\r\nSista Hailstorm\r\n& dj Miss Broadway\r\n \r\nPeace and Light, CARA Community.\r\n\r\nLooking for some fire and spice to set a strong year’s end?  Join us for the 2009’s final Ladies First THIS coming Saturday.  It will be a night of mind opening inspiration with features Geneiva Arunga and\r\nSista Hailstorm with dj Miss Broadway on the decks.\r\n\r\nPlease encourage sister friends to come get on the open-mic @ 8pm; or sister crafts/artists to bring their work to the open marketplace.\r\n \r\n\r\nThis Saturday’s featured artists:\r\n \r\n\r\nGeneiva Arunga is a gifted young artist, community organizer and scholar wise beyond her years. Her poetry is truthful and unapologetic utilizing art as a platform to open minds and initiate change. As a youth activist, Geneiva is involved with a number of organizations within the Seattle area. \r\nSista Hailstorm has spent much time over the past several years traveling around the world ripping up stages.  A powerful visionary and deeply rounded artist, her style and voice bring new energy to a revolutionary movement.  Her work consciously touches the restoring of balance; healing; and training the strongest physical, mental and spiritual self.\r\nDJ Miss Broadway started deejaying in the mid-90’s on pirate radio, house parties, and local fund raisers using cassette tapes and vinyl. She has been deejaying at Seattle dance clubs and bars since 2001 using vinyl, playing music of all sorts, mainly from the 1960’s – the 1990’s.  DJ Miss Broadway has the most fun spinnin’ Underground Hip Hop and Disco, though her heart is mainly with Jazz.\r\n\r\n------------------