(611, 269, '2009-12-22 18:29:28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'I''m a 24 year old guitarist, and I''m looking for someone with whom I can collaborate. Specifically, I''m looking for a vocalist. If you play an instrument, that''s a plus. I''m influenced largely by so-called alternative and "indie" music.  I''m also interested in some electronic and experimental music. Just to give you an idea, I especially love Stereolab, Sonic Youth, and Portishead. If you''re interested, please reply, and I can direct you to some samples of some of my works in progress. If you''d like to contribute to them or start something new, great! I''m also up for contributing to your works in progress if you''re interested. Thanks!', 'In search of vocalist/musical collaborator', 0, '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-12-22 18:29:28', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=611', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(612, 14, '2009-12-29 14:23:19', '2009-12-29 22:23:19', '<p>With 2010 fast approaching, I have a new year resolution I''d like to share with all you fine folks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All over the country, there are basements, grange halls, teen centers, warehouses, back rooms of pizza shops, living rooms and converted store-fronts where people gather for shows. Like SDIY, youth-driven spaces work on the belief that young people are more than just consumers of culture: they''re the creators, too. Some of these are organized by a dedicated collective, but most of them don''t exist in a city like Seattle where the battle over all-ages music has already been waged, and a permanent venue like <a href="http://www.theveraproject.org/">The Vera Project</a> exists. But each year, many of them will have to close in the face of scared local governments, police, and a lack of resources.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That''s why in 2005, Vera, Music For America (now defunct), <a href="http://www.youthmovementrecords.org/">Youth Movement Records</a> and <a href="http://www.youthspeaks.org/">Youth Speaks SF</a> came together to form the <a href="http://www.allagesmovementproject.org/">All-Ages Movement Project</a>. Though our organizations are all very different, we envisioned a national network of like-minded organizations that would share the best practices, inspiration, models; a culture where young people, whether the performers or the fans, never have to hear, "sorry, this show is 21+."</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Currently, AMP functions as an online directory of existing all-ages projects around the country, and a resource for folks who want to start their own project, and need advice for keeping an all-ages venue alive. In early 2010, AMP will also publish <a id="i.e2" title="In Every Town: An All Ages Music Manualfesto" href="http://www.allagesmovementproject.org/book">In Every Town: An All Ages Music Manualfesto</a>: documentation of the ways that people in different cities have created space for young people in the music community, as well as a guide for everyone else who wants to do it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My resolution for 2010 is thus: I''ve pledged $10 a month to both <a id="t46s" title="Vera" href="https://www.paypal.com/cgi-bin/webscr?cmd=_xclick&amp;business=vanessag@theveraproject.org&amp;no_shipping=0&amp;no_note=1&amp;tax=0&amp;currency_co">Vera</a> and <a id="eans" title="donate!" href="http://allagesmovementproject.org/donate_redirect">AMP</a>, because I can''t imagine what my life would have been like without all-ages shows. And to celebrate the release of the AMP manualfesto, I''m going to highlight all-ages and youth-driven spaces here on the SDIY blog. <strong>I''ll donate $10 to these projects, and I challenge you to do the same.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only we know what the true value of always all-ages music and art is in our communities. Ten dollars might not seem like much, but at the same time, when you''re young, unemployed, or struggling from paycheck to paycheck, $10 can be a pretty significant donation. And to a small arts organization, or a collective working under the radar, it can also mean a whole lot. Giving young people the access and skills to produce music is more than just an after-school art project. It''s a political statement against the way youth culture is represented in mass media.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SeattleDIY has always focused on building and promoting the DIY projects, ethos and communities in our little wet city. But like AMP, we can also be a platform for spreading that momentum out. To build a culture that values art and music, that supports the places and the projects that bring that music to life, and fuels do-it-yourself and do-it-together action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trial were probably talking about the straightedge hardcore community, but I found it pretty applicable when they said, "Make this a movement again, instead of only a scene."</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you want to get in touch with me about this, hit me up at: parkranger[at]gmail[dot]com. And for full disclosure: I''m a paid grantwriter at Vera, and we share office-space with AMP.</p>', 'Always all-ages: supporting youth-driven spaces in every ''hood', 0, 'With 2010 fast approaching, I have a new year resolution I''d like to share with all you fine folks.\r\n\r\nAll over the country, there are basements, grange halls, teen centers, warehouses, back rooms of pizza shops, living rooms and converted store-fronts where people gather for shows. Like SDIY, youth-driven spaces work on the belief that young people are more than just consumers of culture: they''re the creators, too. Some of these are organized by a dedicated collective, but most of them don''t exist in a city like Seattle where the battle over all-ages music has already been waged, and a permanent venue like The Vera Project exists. But each year, many of them will have to close in the face of scared local governments, police, and a lack of resources. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'always-all-ages-supporting-youth-driven-spaces-in-every-hood', '', '', '2009-12-29 14:23:19', '2009-12-29 22:23:19', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=612', 0, 'post', '', 0);
