(616, 271, '2009-12-30 21:15:53', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '<p>Hey, I''m the M-F cook at Perinatal Treatment Center in North Seattle (on the #5 and #358 bus routes). We''re looking for a relief cook to work every saturday, sunday, most holidays and random times (with notice) when I take a vacation or something.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I''m posting it here because I think someone with a FNB background or similar food philosophy would be best for the job. Those are the skills that have come in handy the most for me -- cooking for large groups, improvising (about half our ingredients are from weekly donations and the rest we purchase), working on a small budget, having a big ol'' heart and wanting everybody to get great, healthy food.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I cook veg*n M-F so the facility specifically wants someone who will cook meat meals on the weekends. We do get a lot of meat donations, and I would love a cook who could work with that as much as possible instead of having to purchase a lot of meat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>job description my boss wrote up:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perinatal Treatment Services looking for a part time cook.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Help turn lives around and build stronger families! Work at a 26-bed residential chemical dependency treatment program for pregnant and parenting women.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seeking a kitchen professional to fill our Relief Cook Position in our North Seattle location (130th and Aurora).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ideal candidate is reliable, creative, and has the ability to prepare/serve lunch and dinner for 26 women and up to 17 children. Needs to love real food, have patience, good boundaries and love people!!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hours are 9:30 am – 5:30 pm Saturdays and Sundays. Work hours may also include occasional holidays to cover for the full time cook.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Lead cook serves a vegetarian diet 5 days a week so candidate must be able to prepare meat dishes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will insure the DOH procedures and regulations regarding storage, transporting, and preparations are followed. Background training highly recommended. Equal Opportunity Employer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Candidate must be able to demonstrate no alcohol or drug misuse for 3 years prior to employment, and no misuse while employed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Starting pay $11.50 DOE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Email cover letter and resume asap to darcyf@ptswa.org and also vegancookies@gmail.com (both email addresses are mine.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>--Darcy</p>', 'Part-time job cooking for ladies/kids at a residential drug treatment center', 0, '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2009-12-30 21:15:53', '2009-12-31 05:15:53', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=616', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(617, 271, '2009-12-29 19:09:50', '2009-12-30 03:09:50', 'Hey, I''m the M-F cook at Perinatal Treatment Center in North Seattle (on the #5 and #358 bus routes). We''re looking for a relief cook to work every saturday, sunday, most holidays and random times (with notice) when I take a vacation or something.\n\nI''m posting it here because I think someone with a FNB background or similar food philosophy would be best for the job. Those are the skills that have come in handy the most for me -- cooking for large groups, improvising (about half our ingredients are from weekly donations and the rest we purchase), working on a small budget, having a big ol'' heart and wanting everybody to get great, healthy food.\n\nI cook veg*n M-F so the facility specifically wants someone who will cook meat meals on the weekends. We do get a lot of meat donations, and I would love a cook who could work with that as much as possible instead of having to purchase a lot of meat.\n\njob description my boss wrote up:\n\nPerinatal Treatment Services looking for a part time cook.\n\nHelp turn lives around and build stronger families! Work at a 26-bed residential chemical dependency treatment program for pregnant and parenting women.\n\nSeeking a kitchen professional to fill our Relief Cook Position in our North Seattle location (130th and Aurora).\n\nThe ideal candidate is reliable, creative, and has the ability to prepare/serve lunch and dinner for 26 women and up to 17 children. Needs to love real food, have patience, good boundaries and love people!!\n\nHours are 9:30 am – 5:30 pm Saturdays and Sundays. Work hours may also include occasional holidays to cover for the full time cook.\n\nThe Lead cook serves a vegetarian diet 5 days a week so candidate must be able to prepare meat dishes.\n\nWill insure the DOH procedures and regulations regarding storage, transporting, and preparations are followed. Background training highly recommended. Equal Opportunity Employer.\n\nCandidate must be able to demonstrate no alcohol or drug misuse for 3 years prior to employment, and no misuse while employed.\n\nStarting pay $11.50 DOE \n\nEmail cover letter and resume asap to darcyf@ptswa.org and also vegancookies@gmail.com (both email addresses are mine.)\n\n--Darcy', 'Part-time job cooking for ladies/kids at a residential drug treatment center', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '616-revision', '', '', '2009-12-29 19:09:50', '2009-12-30 03:09:50', '', 616, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=617', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(618, 273, '2010-01-05 11:47:02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Hey my name is Leland Corley and I''m working on building a website that will provide booking information, venue locations, and other necessary information. I will also include links to sites that stream music such as Pandora, Lala, justhearit, projectplaylist, and seeqpod. There will be a blog section to this website that will give bands a chance to collaborate in a sort of band pool esque fashion. My aim with this project is to help local bands thrive in the contemporary music sceneand to promote musical learning. I was wondering if it would be at all possible to collaborate with the adminisatrators of this site in order to get an idea of how to set up an effective web site and blog. I would also like to work with Seattle DIY because Seattle''s local bands embody the spirit of doing things themselves.', 'Website for up and coming local bands', 0, '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2010-01-05 11:47:02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=618', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(619, 1, '2010-01-08 12:27:04', '2010-01-08 20:27:04', 'I just read about this on <a href="http://profanityhill.blogspot.com">Profanity Hill </a>(http://profanityhill.blogspot.com/), a new blog about local Seattle zine culture, as well as an online distro for zines. This blog is super exciting, and is a must-read for people who want to get more connected to the resurgence of zine culture. If anyone wants to share other local/northwest zine distros, leave a comment about it (<a href="http://msvaleriepark.blogspot.com/">Ms Valerie Park Distro</a> is another great one that I can think of off the top of my head).\r\n\r\nAnyway, here''s the event that was mentioned on Profanity Hill:\r\n\r\n--------------------\r\n\r\nLarge, Hairy and Literate: Zinesters and Artists Celebrate Bigfoot\r\nThursday, January 14, 5–8 p.m. in ZAPP (at the Richard Hugo House)\r\n\r\nWell before "Harry and the Hendersons" hit the big screen, the Pacific Northwest has had an obsession with Bigfoot, beginning with Lummi tales of ape-like, cannibalistic wildmen to the Sonics'' former fur-balled mascot, Squatch.\r\n\r\nContinuing the legacy, ZAPP presents a group exhibit featuring new work that draws upon both visual and literary interpretations of Bigfoot lore by local artists David Lasky, Kinoko, Kelly Froh, Greg Hofmann and Darin Shuler, among others, in conjunction with Blitz!: Capitol Hill''s Art Walk.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the exhibit, ZAPP will showcase zines and comics from the archive that focus on tales or histories of the Bigfoot phenomenon in the Pacific Northwest. Visitors are encouraged to donate their own Bigfoot zines or comics and are invited to participate in on-site drawing and storytelling. For more information about the ZAPP gallery, email zapp@hugohouse.org.\r\n', 'Large, Hairy and Literate: Zinesters and Artists Celebrate Bigfoot', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'large-hairy-and-literate-zinesters-and-artists-celebrate-bigfoot', '', '', '2010-01-08 12:27:04', '2010-01-08 20:27:04', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=619', 0, 'post', '', 0),
