(759, 1, '2010-03-10 12:45:31', '2010-03-10 20:45:31', 'Whoa. On <a href="http://boingboing.net">Boing Boing!</a> (a great blog), they posted that Google Maps now includes the ability to find directions for bikes. While this is great news for us bicyclists, what are other non-google options for finding the best ways of getting around town on our noble steeds? \r\n\r\nWell, lookie here: <a href="http://www.cityofseattle.net/transportation/bikemaps.htm">http://www.cityofseattle.net/transportation/bikemaps.htm</a>\r\nand here: <a href="http://www.cascade.org/community/maps_routes.cfm">http://www.cascade.org/community/maps_routes.cfm</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.boingboing.net/2010/03/10/google-maps-goes-bik.html">From Boing Boing: </a>\r\n<em>"Bicycle" is now an option for mode of transport in Google maps. Ostensibly, the directions given will help you avoid particularly nasty car traffic and particularly disheartening elevation changes, though<a href="http://www.treehugger.com/files/2010/03/woot-google-adds-bike-there-feature-to-google-maps-video.php"> Treehugger found some kinks</a> in that when they tried to plot a route across San Francisco. There''s not enough uphill slogs in Minneapolis (and I don''t know St. Paul well enough) to get you a real solid second opinion from the Twin Cities. But it was smart enough to not send theoretical me biking straight up the feels-like-45-degree incline of 14th street when asked for directions to the University of Kansas journalism school (see above).\r\n\r\nIt also shows dedicated bike trails and bike lanes, to help plan the trip.\r\n\r\nHow''s this work for your hometown?\r\n</em>\r\n\r\nOf course, a great DIY community resource that we can''t get enough of is <a href="http://www.thebikery.org/">The Bikery</a>. They''re seriously awesome, for a million reasons. They have a few classes coming up:\r\n<em>Wheels Class - Sundays, March 7th & March 14th from noon-2pm\r\n\r\nEver wondered what makes up a wheel? Pondered what "truing" is all about? Want the ability to build up a set of wheels? Well all these answers and more will be covered in this two day wheels class! So come one come all and we''ll really get you rolling. Ba-dum-bum!! (Attending both sessions in suggested.)\r\n\r\nGetting Back in the Saddle - March 21st from noon-2pm\r\n\r\nHaven''t ridden a bike since you were a kid, but looking to get "back in the saddle"? This is the class for you! We''ll go over information helpful to new cyclists like which bikes are best for which purpose, good places to buy bikes, what other equipment you need to get started, how to ride on streets, and we''ll have time to answer questions that you bring as well.</em>\r\n\r\n\r\nAnd on a side note, does anyone know what''s currently going on with <a href="http://www.bikeshack.org/">The Bike Shack</a>? I haven''t been there in a while, and now that Wayward Cafe moved to the Ave, I figured that it''s now no more. Updates?', 'BICYCLE! BICYCLE!', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bicycle-bicycle', '', '', '2010-03-10 12:45:31', '2010-03-10 20:45:31', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=759', 0, 'post', '', 2),
