(893, 1, '2010-04-12 10:25:12', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '\r\nI don''t often do "editorial" type posts on this website, but I feel that doing this one is appropriate.\r\n\r\nI just attended the <a href="http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=822">protest against police brutality</a> that just took place today (read about it <a href="http://www.capitolhillseattle.com/2010/04/09/protest-against-police-brutality-starts-at-seattle-central">here </a>and <a href="http://slog.thestranger.com/slog/archives/2010/04/09/the-police-accountability-march">here</a>), and I was given flyers published by folks regarding the action. One thing I was given disturbed me: a pamphlet entitled "Some People Shoot Back", which describes Christopher Monfort and his acts of counter-violence against a member of the SPD. While I somewhat appreciate critical and provocative discourse of ideas and challenges to institutions of power and violence, I became upset when I saw the back of the flyer, which listed "Resources for getting involved". Listed on there was SeattleDIY.com, this very website. I would like to state unequivocally that SeattleDIY should not be seen as a resource to get involved in insurrection and violence against the state/against police. The DIY culture, community, and movement is not about "Doing [acts of violence] Yourself", rather DIY is about coming up with creative solutions that make our lives more fulfilling, more engaged, and more empowered. While there are certainly parallel values that DIY shares with anarchist theory, I personally do not see reclamation of violence as one of them - I would like to believe that this is a movement based around creativity, not destruction. And while I personally am disgusted with the routine acts of violence by the police and by the state against vulnerable and marginalized people all over, and while I personally would like to do what I can to resist these institutions and build a future free of domination and oppression, I do not think it was appropriate to associate the name of this website with an inflammatory and provocative pamphlet that seems to advocate and endorse acts of physical violence against members of the police department. Such advocacy and endorsement are not part of this website or the mission of the people who run it. In the future, please contact me, the maintainer of this website, before associating it with similarly controversial materials in the future. \r\n\r\nSo, to be clear: as the webmaster and moderator of this website, I appreciate and support the dialogue and actions of people who want to make a more empowered and accountable society by way of protest and direct action, but personally don''t see this site as a resource to become more involved in committing acts of violence against members of the state/police. As I see it, this is not the appropriate forum for that particular brand of activism. The SeattleDIY.com website and the other things we publish are utilized by a large and diverse community, and endorsements of a tactics, political views, etc, should not be considered representative of the DIY movement as a whole. The DIY movement is large, nebulous, and diverse, and much of it celebrates canning and pickling done by conservative Mormons as much as efforts made by folk who want to create more accountable communities that don''t need the police/jails/prisons. The ideals and values here are not monolithic, and should understood and a reflection of a particular approach to both social change and daily living, rather than a prescription for specific activities or ideologies.\r\n\r\nI hope this is clear and understandable, and I hope none of what I''ve written here disappoints any members of the DIY movement. If anyone would like to have dialogue about this, reply to this post, or email me directly at sdiycollective at gmail dot com. Thanks for reading.\r\n\r\n***this has been edited as of 4/10/10 to reflect insights and address concerns made by people in the community. Thanks for your input.***', 'old protest response.', 0, '', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2010-04-12 10:25:12', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=893', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(857, 1, '2010-04-09 13:56:53', '2010-04-09 21:56:53', 'I don''t often do "editorial" type posts on this website, but I feel that doing this one is appropriate.\n\nI just attended the <a href="http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=822">protest against police brutality</a> that just took place today (read about it <a href="http://www.capitolhillseattle.com/2010/04/09/protest-against-police-brutality-starts-at-seattle-central">here </a>and <a href="http://slog.thestranger.com/slog/archives/2010/04/09/the-police-accountability-march">here</a>), and I was given flyers published by folks regarding the action. One thing I was given disturbed me: a pamphlet entitled "Some People Shoot Back", which describes Christopher Monfort and his acts of counter-violence against a member of the SPD. While I somewhat appreciate critical and provocative discourse of ideas and challenges to institutions of power and violence, I became upset when I saw the back of the flyer, which listed "Resources for getting involved". Listed on there was SeattleDIY.com, this very website. I would like to state unequivocally that SeattleDIY is not a resource to get involved in insurrection and violence against the state/against police. The DIY culture, community, and movement is not about "Doing [acts of violence] Yourself", rather DIY is about coming up with creative solutions that make our lives more fulfilling, more engaged, and more empowered. While there are certainly parallel values that DIY shares with anarchist theory, reclamation of violence is not one of them - this is a movement based around creativity, not destruction. And while *I* personally am disgusted with the routine acts of violence by the police and by the state against vulnerable and marginalized people all over, and while *I* personally would like to do what I can to resist these institutions and build a future free of domination and oppression, I do *NOT* feel comfortable with the DIY movement being coopted by anyone who would advocate for violence against other people, regardless of how complicit to crimes against marginalized communities that person may be. \n\nSo, to be clear: I/we appreciate and support the dialogue and actions of people who want to make a more empowered and accountable society by way of protest and (non-violent) direct action, but I/we are NOT a resource to become more involved in committing acts of violence against members of the state/police. This is simply not the forum for that kind of rhetoric. The SeattleDIY.com website and the other things we publish are utilized by a large and diverse community, and again, we will not be coopted by a very small portion of this community. We celebrate canning and pickling done by conservative Mormons as much as we celebrate efforts made by folk who want to create more accountable communities that don''t need the police/jails/prisons. Our ideals and values are not monolithic, and should not be conveyed as though they are.\n\nI hope this is clear and understandable, and I hope none of what I''ve written here disappoints any fans of the DIY movement. If anyone would like to have dialogue about this, reply to this post, or email me directly at sdiycollective at gmail dot com.', 'April 9th police brutality protest, and a response to the literature handed out.', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '856-revision', '', '', '2010-04-09 13:56:53', '2010-04-09 21:56:53', '', 856, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=857', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(858, 11, '2010-04-09 17:40:46', '2010-04-10 01:40:46', '<a href=''http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZHrn5sSI0gM''>March Against Police Brutality March: Arrest Footage</a>\r\n\r\nReporting of the incidents of the March Against Police Brutality on April 9th, 2010. Reported by Seattle Independent Media Center\r\n<!--more-->\r\n\r\nThree people were arrested during a march against Police Brutality in Seattle WA, this afternoon around 1:30 p.m. The march was organized in solidarity with the recent shooting of a Portland OR. resident by police, and with actions in response to this murder occurring up and down the West Coast. \r\n\r\nAround 100 people met in front of Seattle Community College at noon. Police presence was already significant with 4 cops on horses, approximately a dozen cops on bicycles, with squad cars scattered around the surrounding blocks, as well as officers watching from inside SCC buildings.\r\n\r\nDemonstrators started moving around 12:40, initially staying on the sidewalk while occasionally moving to block traffic as the march snaked through Capitol Hill.\r\n\r\nMarchers took the street at 11th and Pine, blocking traffic before being pushed onto the sidewalk by police officers with bikes. After circling the block, protestors attempted to move a small dumpster into the street but were stopped by mounted police, who tried to use their horses to physically harm the protestors. The march grew quiet after this confrontation but people seemed determined to continue.\r\n\r\nAs the march moved up Pine, protestors again tried to move a large dumpster into the street but were stopped immediately by police. Marchers were violently pushed aside as cops used bicycles to barricade 3 individuals against the wall of Rancho Bravo, Mexican restaurant.  A female-bodied person was slammed into a concrete pole and pushed to the ground.\r\n\r\nThe three people clung together on the ground as the cops tried to tear them apart. Other officers blocked off the rest of the march and attempted to block cameras from the scene.\r\n\r\nThe first person arrested was seen being restrained by three cops, each with a knee in his back, legs and head. He was dragged limp to a waiting police van.\r\n\r\nThe second arrestee was female-bodied and was taken to a separate squad car. While being forced into the car, she asked the press to photograph and document injuries to her face. The police would not let reporters into the street to take photos, but she appeared to have scratches and cuts on her right eye and chin, as well as the left side of her face.\r\n\r\nObservers say they witnessed the third individual being kicked in the head by officers while on the ground. Presumably due to injuries he sustained, he did not seem lucid while being taken into custody.\r\n\r\nThe march continued on down Broadway until dispersing around 2:30. Jail support is being organized. The police have not released any information on who or exactly how many people have been arrested, though the Seattle Times (who has the corporate privilege of being in contact with police) reports that “Seattle Police spokeswoman Renee Witt said the five were arrested during a march in the Capitol Hill neighborhood Friday afternoon for investigation of crimes ranging from trespassing to inciting a riot”  \r\n\r\nOur hearts go out to our friends in custody\r\n\r\nIn Solidarity,\r\nSeattle Independent Media Center\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'March Against Police Brutality April 9, 2010', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'march-against-police-brutality-april-9-2010', '', '', '2010-04-10 18:10:35', '2010-04-11 02:10:35', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=858', 0, 'post', '', 1),
