(896, 1, '2010-04-15 11:33:51', '2010-04-15 19:33:51', 'I''ve noticed a lot of new exciting projects coming about that are taking advantage of new internet-based social networks and once disparate communities now strengthened by the greater visibility of our peers via blogs (for example, I''m especially excited by blogs like <a href="http://vegansofcolor.wordpress.com/">Vegans of Color</a>, and <a href="http://nativeappropriations.blogspot.com/">Native Appropriations</a>). It only makes sense that the radical self-publishing ideas developed during the 80''s & 90''s of the zine revolution would start to really develop and inform this new blog movement. \r\n\r\nWe''ve had a couple posts on here about the awesome <a href="http://www.throughthiswindow.com">Through This Window</a> webzine before. Well, their next issue (TTW002: "Unrequited Love") is coming out soon, and their deadline is May 15th. They''re seeking any kind of content that you may want to make - video, essay, illustrative, whateves! Here''s their brief description of the upcoming issue:\r\n"First crushes, fantasies/daydreams, "just friends", love letters to strangers, reactions to professing of love, where did things go wrong?, etc. etc.  Please submit by 5/15 for a 6/1 release!"\r\n\r\nI also just found out about <a href="http://blogs.evergreen.edu/feministvideozine/">Double Take!</a>, a webzine started by Evergreen students and friends. It looks aaaamazing!\r\n"Double Take! is a show about and by DIY and Feminist artists, musicians, and social justice workers. We call it a ‘Feminist Video Zine’ because our media content is inspired by zine aesthetics and DIY ethos... Our show features live interviews, segments on DIY art projects and Feminist history, and musical performances. It will be shot at The Evergreen State College in the new HD television studio, the CCAM.\r\nIf you are interested in being a guest or submitting your own work to be included in a “webisode” or on-air programing, you can contact us at feministvideozine@gmail.com!"\r\n<a href="http://blogs.evergreen.edu/feministvideozine/"><img src="http://blogs.evergreen.edu/feministvideozine/files/2010/01/1.png" alt="" width="400"/></a>\r\n\r\nOf course, print zines are still going strong, and have even seen a resurgence in recent years. I posted the other day about "<a href="http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=885">International Girl Gang Underground</a>", which is looking for submissions for people interested in the lasting legacy of the Riot Grrl movement. \r\nI also just got an email from the zine <a href="http://www.givemeback.org/">Give Me Back</a>, which is having a new issue coming out soon, and are looking to take ads from the DIY community to help fund their awesome cheap/free zine. If you''re not familiar with Give Me Back, I would recommend checking it out. They were born following the death of the influential zine <a href="http://www.ebullition.com/hac.html">Heart Attack</a>, and have had some really incredible pieces on activist groups like <a href="http://www.phillyspissed.net/">Philly''s Pissed</a>, the <a href="http://www.myspace.com/downtherehealth">Down There Health Collective</a>, and cool bands like Des_Ark and Margaret Thrasher.\r\n\r\nAnyway, I''ll get off my soapbox about things I''m excited about. I hope readers of this site check out what these great folk are up to, contribute to these projects, and start their own!', 'New media // webzines on the rise!', 0, '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-media-webzines-on-the-rise', '', '\nhttp://www.seattlediy.com/?p=885', '2010-04-15 11:34:23', '2010-04-15 19:34:23', '', 0, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=896', 0, 'post', '', 0),
