ideozine@gmail.com!"\n<a href="http://blogs.evergreen.edu/feministvideozine/"><img src="http://blogs.evergreen.edu/feministvideozine/files/2010/01/1.png" alt="" /></a>\n\nOf course, print zines are still going strong, and have even seen a resurgence in recent years. I posted the other day about "<a href="http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=885">International Girl Gang Underground</a>", which is looking for submissions for people interested in the lasting legacy of the Riot Grrl movement. \nI also just got an email from the zine <a href="http://www.givemeback.org/">Give Me Back</a>, which is having a new issue coming out soon, and are looking to take ads from the DIY community to help fund their awesome cheap/free zine. If you''re not familiar with Give Me Back, I would recommend checking it out. They were born following the death of the influential zine <a href="http://www.ebullition.com/hac.html">Heart Attack</a>, and have had some really incredible pieces on activist groups like <a href="http://www.phillyspissed.net/">Philly''s Pissed</a>, the <a href="http://www.myspace.com/downtherehealth">Down There Health Collective</a>, and cool bands like Des_Ark and Margaret Thrasher.\n\nAnyway, I''ll get off my soapbox about things I''m excited about. I hope readers of this site check out what these great folk are up to, contribute to these projects, and start their own!', 'New media // webzines on the rise!', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '896-autosave', '', '', '2010-04-15 11:33:53', '2010-04-15 19:33:53', '', 896, 'http://www.seattlediy.com/?p=898', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
