INSERT INTO `wp_sfmessages` (`message_id`, `sent_date`, `from_id`, `to_id`, `title`, `message`, `message_status`, `inbox`, `sentbox`, `is_reply`, `message_slug`) VALUES
(1, '2009-12-11 23:27:42', 267, 183, 'Keyboardist/Multi-instrumentalist', '<p>Hey there,</p>\r\n<p>I&#39;m entirely interested in hearing more about your group.</p>\r\n<p>I might be able to add the dimension you need. You sound as though you&#39;re a pretty solid group, so I wouldn&#39;t want to hinder your endeavor by being subpar, but if you&#39;re genuinely interested, you can hear how I might be able to contribute:</p>\r\n<p>http://www.myspace.com/viamemo</p>\r\n<p>- Jay</p>', 0, 1, 1, 0, 'keyboardistmulti-instrumentalist'),
(2, '2010-07-22 09:24:44', 329, 305, 'dr glorious indeed!', '<p>hi amanda</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>my name&#39;s bryan! i actually posted a few threads down about my quest for housing in seattle, and the space you&#39;ve described sounds like it might be right up my alley! i totally appreciate that y&#39;all are trying to maintain a gender balance in the house (we&#39;ve faced the same dilemma when interviewing new mates at my current digs), but I figured I&#39;d give this a shot because I&#39;d really like to live in a shared space that encourages projecting and crafty meddling and good cooking and responsible, communicative healthy friendships!</p>\r\n<p>My post on this board has a lot of personal information about me and my situation, so it might be easiest for you to look that over (i&#39;m the one called \\"looking for affordable collective housing/advice\\", but to sum things up i&#39;m a fairly quiet, gender-suspicious boy-creature who&#39;s lived in washington dc proper for nearly a decade and grew up outside the city. I&#39;ve been involved in all kinds of DIY music/performance/teaching-type projects during my time here and I&#39;m looking for an inspiring change in my surroundings. I&#39;ve lived in collective/group houses for basically my entire adult life (i&#39;m 27) and I&#39;d love to continue that manner of residing in Seattle.</p>\r\n<p>I&#39;m hoping to move into town on Sept 1, so if there was a chance I could live with y&#39;all I&#39;d be happy to pre-pay rent in Mid August in anticipation of my slightly-late arrival. I&#39;m coming to Seattle with a chunk of money saved up so I can float for a couple of months while I find decent work, and I&#39;m excited to immerse myself in the lives and works and projects of a new community of weird,lovely folks - hopefully for the next several years of my strange time on this strange ballistic rock.</p>\r\n<p>The immediate catch, of course, is that I wouldn&#39;t be able to meet y&#39;all in person beforehand, but I&#39;d be happy to do a phone interview or conference call or , uh, video chat or whatever makes sense to help you get a better sense of where I&#39;m at and what kind of energy and interests I could maybe bring to the space! I&#39;m also excited to learn more about you and your housemates!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Anyhow, that&#39;s where i&#39;m at! If I can answer any more questions to help yr process please let me know.. in the meantime, take care, and i hope to hear back from ya!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>xob</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 1, 1, 1, 0, 'dr-glorious-indeed'),
(3, '2010-07-22 16:39:09', 328, 305, 'inquiring within', '<p>Hi Amanda,</p>\r\n<p>I saw yr post and had to respond -- The Office of Dr Glorious sounds pretty much amazing. &nbsp;I&#39;m about to start a job as an experiential nutrition educator (think: afterschool cooking clubs, school gardening workshops, hands-on learning, etcetc) at a south Seattle public school, via Solid Ground; it would be so excellent to live with others who also work with kids, are based in the CD, value collective housing, and have a mind for DIY.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>More about me: I&#39;m a tiny, queer, female-identified person of color, 22, who loves to read, cook (not very well, but I&#39;m working on it!), mess around in gardens, and cobble together setlists for her radio show. &nbsp;I&#39;m coming in from Baltimore, where I&#39;ve spent time working at Red Emma&#39;s Bookstore &amp; Coffeehouse (a radical, collectively run infoshop in the city) an urban garden called Participation Park. &nbsp;I&#39;m excited to crashland in Seattle and join forces with groups like FNB, Hollow Earth Radio, Books to Prisoners, CARA, and A/PI organizations. &nbsp;Sharing space, respecting boundaries, and supporting people/their projects are all very important to me, and I&#39;m especially energized by connecting with folks who are interested in creating careful, accountable communities, too.</p>\r\n<p>(And I can wash dishes! You should see me! I&#39;m quite a dedicated dishwasher, particularly after living in a house where everyone seemed to fear the sponge. &nbsp;Nope, not me. &nbsp;Love the sponge. &nbsp;Love the empty sink.)</p>\r\n<p>Work in Baltimore wraps up for me on 13 August, and I&#39;m planning to head west as soon as possible. &nbsp;The nutrition job in Seattle is an AmeriCorps position, which means that I&#39;m getting paid a pretty small salary. &nbsp;I was getting nervous that Seattle housing would be way too expensive, but $310-360 is perfect! Ahh! Relief!</p>\r\n<p>If any of this seems appealing to you, living-wise, please let me know! I&#39;d love to talk on the phone, if that would be easier. &nbsp;If you wanted to meet before making any decisions, I could crash at my aunt&#39;s place so that we can figure things out in person. &nbsp;Just let me know either way!</p>\r\n<p>Please&amp;Thankyou,<br />Jen&nbsp;</p>', 0, 1, 1, 0, 'inquiring-within'),
(4, '2010-08-03 14:58:22', 336, 328, 'Tukwila House', '<p>Hey Bean,</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p>This is Matthew; I&#39;m the one who has started the new collective with Christopher and Bethany. I&#39;m not 100% sure how fast our responses have been and I apologize for that, things have just been crazy for all three of us, Christopher and Bethany just left for a small trip and we just moved in the new house a few nights ago and I&rsquo;ve been super busy with house stuff. But anyways, we had&nbsp;saw your post and thought you&#39;d be a fantastic addition and from what I&#39;ve read Christopher has already laid a lot down on what we are going for and trying to do with the house.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I understand that you might be concerned with how far it is&nbsp; out of Seattle correct? It&#39;s definitely a 20 to 25 minute bus ride and depending on what time of day you leave the house there are other buses that go straight to Seattle. But these are regular metros and not sound transits which is good. Having a bike will also make things a lot easier and faster and if not&nbsp;we have extra bikes for housemates to use.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Even though the house isn&#39;t in the city there are a lot of good things about being out here, one is that our house is in a rural area so there isn&#39;t a whole lot going around and there is a lot more trees and nature to enjoy, plus how much garden space we have. There is a lot of space in this area for really cheap, idk if they mentioned anything about the cost but rent would be around $300 with us four in it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Sorry my internet access is limited (in the middle of moving still) but we are very interested in meeting you and if your here in Seattle I&#39;d love to show you the house so you can see for yourself how far it is from the city and if you&rsquo;re interested or not. We hope to hear back from you!</p>\r\n<p>-Matthew</p>\r\n<p>206-786-5397</p>', 1, 1, 1, 0, 'tukwila-house'),
(5, '2010-08-08 18:44:09', 328, 336, 'Tukwila House', '<p>Hey Matthew!</p>\r\n<p>I only just realized that I had a PM; sorry for the delay! I hope moving was a raging success (despite the requisite stressfulness). &nbsp;I&#39;m in the process of packing/selling/destroying/distributing my stuff out here in Baltimore, which is NO PICNIC let me be the latest to say.</p>\r\n<p>Thanks also for all the extra info about yr rad-sounding house. &nbsp;I&#39;m planning to fly out to Seattle this Saturday and crash on a couch for the week, so maybe I could visit and introduce myself, if that&#39;s alright with y&#39;all?</p>\r\n<p>$300 is hard to pass up rent-wise, and the three of you sound like amazing folks. &nbsp;I will say right off the bat that I&#39;m looking into a few houses at this point, so I definitely can&#39;t commit o anything... but I do appreciate your messages and if it isn&#39;t too much trouble for me to swing by sometime after the 14th, it would be great to meet you &amp; the house!</p>\r\n<p>Let me know what you think!</p>\r\n<p>Jen</p>', 1, 1, 1, 1, 'tukwila-house'),
(6, '2010-08-09 19:50:05', 336, 328, 'Tukwila House', '<p>Yes, that sounds awesome! We&#39;ll be here waitin&#39; for you.</p>\r\n<p>I believe we sent you another message last night, through email, it just has more info about the house, area, etc. But anyways,&nbsp;we will look forward to your arrival and I&#39;m glad to hear you have other options on the table for you to choose from. It&#39;s funny that you say that you&#39;ll be here on the 14th cause I had moved here from my home town and I got here on that day exactly one year ago, ha.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>But yeah, just give us a call whenever you want to come check out the place and we&#39;ll prepare a delicious feast! Take care, good luck with the move!</p>\r\n<p>-Matthew</p>\r\n<p>206-786-5397</p>', 1, 1, 1, 1, 'tukwila-house');
